---
// Copy is locked in reducing-valve-identity-kit.md — do not rephrase.
// One deliberate adaptation: the kit's key slot "[Ed25519 public key —
// inserted at Phase 3]" reads as implementer instruction, so the public
// placeholder says "published with the first signed essay" instead.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import NavBar from '../components/NavBar.astro';
import FieldBackground from '../components/FieldBackground.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import { CONTACT_EMAIL } from '../consts';
---

<Base title="About">
  <NavBar />

  <div class="wrap">
    <FieldBackground />
    <div class="inner">

      <main id="main">
        <h1 class="kicker heading">About</h1>

        <blockquote class="epigraph">
          <p>
            “…funnelled through the reducing valve of the brain and nervous system.”
          </p>
          <cite>— Aldous Huxley, <em>The Doors of Perception</em></cite>
        </blockquote>

        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            The Reducing Valve is an independent publication about a single question with many
            disguises: when intelligence becomes abundant, who owns the filter between the world
            and your mind?
          </p>
          <p>
            It covers the agents that will apply for jobs, read feeds, and negotiate on our
            behalf; the platforms and protocols they’ll run on; and the quiet economics
            underneath both, in which employment, attention, and export controls turn out to be
            the same transaction — the purchase of exclusive access to intelligence. One long
            essay a month, occasional shorter notes. Analysis over outrage; mechanics over
            villains.
          </p>
          <p>
            The publication practices what it argues. Every essay is published in a structured,
            machine-readable form alongside the human one, carries a cryptographic signature so
            its provenance can be verified by anyone, and is served to reading agents through an
            open API. If you’ve built a valve of your own, point it here.
          </p>

          <h2 class="section">The author</h2>
          <p>
            Barnaba Barcellona is an AI architect working on enterprise agent systems, based in
            Barcelona. Before that: fine arts, professional kitchens in Copenhagen, and an
            unreasonable number of side projects. He writes here in a personal capacity;
            opinions are his own and not those of any employer.
          </p>

          <h2 class="section">Provenance</h2>
          <p>
            Essays are signed at build time with the key below. Verification instructions live
            in the footer of every essay.
          </p>
          <p class="mono key">[ed25519 public key — published with the first signed essay]</p>

          <h2 class="section">Contact</h2>
          <p>
            <a href={`mailto:${CONTACT_EMAIL}`} class="quiet-link">{CONTACT_EMAIL}</a>
          </p>
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SiteFooter />
</Base>

<style>
  .wrap {
    position: relative;
    isolation: isolate;
  }
  .inner {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 688px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 56px 24px 88px;
  }
  .heading {
    margin: 64px 0 0;
    letter-spacing: 0.28em;
  }
  .epigraph {
    margin: 40px 0 var(--rv-space-lg);
    max-width: var(--rv-measure-quote);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: var(--rv-epigraph-size);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--rv-epigraph-color);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  .epigraph cite {
    font-style: normal;
    font-family: var(--rv-font-sans);
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--rv-text-dim);
  }
  .epigraph cite em {
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .prose {
    font-size: 19px;
  }
  .key {
    background: var(--rv-ink-deep);
    border-radius: var(--rv-radius);
    padding: 14px 18px;
    overflow-wrap: anywhere;
  }
</style>
